<HEADLINE>
<P>
SMALL FACES 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The new House of Blues club on the Sunset Strip, originally scheduled to open 
in March, is now set to have its official inauguration with two invitation-only 
events: a show by club investor Aerosmith on April 22, followed by an April 30 
benefit for the Magic Johnson Foundation featuring the Blues Brothers (Dan 
Aykroyd co-owns the club chain), the Black Crowes, James Brown and John Lee 
Hooker. A full schedule of concerts starts in May. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Two of rap's leading acts have new albums due in July: Chuck D., Flavor Flav 
and crew are working on a new Public Enemy album, while LL Cool J, who 
continues to be one of rap's top-selling artists, is finishing up his latest. . 
. .  
</P>
<P>
 Harry Connick Jr. is said to be returning to his old New Orleans roots for his 
next album, a change from the lighter, jazz-pop flavor of most of his recent 
work. The album is expected in June. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 John Lydon will make an eight-city U.S. book-signing tour for his new 
autobiography, "Rotten: No Irish, No Blacks, No Dogs," including a planned stop 
at West Hollywood's Book Soup on April 21. Lydon, having disbanded Public Image 
Ltd., is also working on his first solo album for Atlantic Records. . . . While 
in town, maybe Lydon can check out the new high-concept L.A. band the Spock 
Pistols -- four guys who dress like "Star Trek's" Mr. Spock and perform only 
Sex Pistols songs. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Booker T. & the MG's' first album in 17 years will be released by Columbia 
Records on May 24. "That's the Way It Should Be" includes instrumental versions 
of U2's "I Still Haven't Found What I'm Looking For," Janet Jackson's "Let's 
Wait a While" and Bob Dylan's "Gotta Serve Somebody," as well as original 
tracks, including the first single, "Cruisin'." . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Ice Cube is setting up a summer concert tour following two spring acting 
stints -- he's starring in John Singleton's "Higher Learning" and an indie film 
titled "Friday." . . . English industrial duo Nitzer Ebb is putting the 
finishing touches on an album now due in September. 
</P>
