<HEADLINE>
<P>
EVICTED BARBERS ARE HEROES FOR HELPING HOMELESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * Jim Carcioppolo and Tom Wilson, featured in "Evicted Barbers Sweep Up for 
Last Time" (March 27), would not remember, but I used to take my two sons in 
for haircuts when they were little. Going into the barbershop was like setting 
foot in the '50s of my childhood.I noticed the old calendars and the ancient 
piano, wondering if anyone ever played it anymore. 
</P>
<P>
 We have lived in this neighborhood for 18 years and never expected to see our 
local barbershop close, and for the most ridiculous of reasons. 
</P>
<P>
 Jim and Tom were part of the solution to the problem of homelessness, giving 
free haircuts and providing a small haven of camaraderie and caring to those 
down on their luck. 
</P>
<P>
 For the landlord to evict them for this reason really stinks! It seems to me 
that the landlord is contributing to the problem. 
</P>
<P>
 He could provide odd jobs for them in the spaces that he rents out. He could 
encourage his tenants to provide discounts for their merchandise and services 
(in return for a rental discount) and he could offer them gift certificates to 
Lucky's (across the street) when they are hungry. 
</P>
<P>
 He could now even consider converting the vacant barbershop into a day shelter 
or donating the space to a food bank or other social service agency. 
</P>
<P>
 Homeless people are just that: people, like all of us. Most of them are not 
dangerous, and the problems they have will not disappear until we treat them 
with dignity. For their gentle kindness, Jim and Tom are quiet heroes to my 
entire family. 
</P>
<P>
 BARBARA SINGER 
</P>
<P>
 North Hollywood 
</P>
</TEXT>
