<HEADLINE>
<P>
TEACHER WILL REMAIN HOSPITALIZED 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 A high school English teacher who became ill after drinking a soda laced with 
cleaning fluid will remain in a Palmdale hospital for another night, hospital 
officials said Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 Susan Ennis felt a burning sensation in her throat and then vomited during 
class Thursday morning at Littlerock High School after she drank from a can of 
soda. 
</P>
<P>
 Ennis told doctors that she feared someone poured dry-erase board cleaner into 
her drink because she had a bottle of the cleaner near her opened drink, said 
Cindy Reid, a spokeswoman for Palmdale Hospital Medical Center. Sheriff's 
reports noted that the can smelled of cleaning fluid. 
</P>
<P>
 Reid said doctors were keeping the 32-year-old teacher to run further 
gastrointestinal tests, including checks to determine whether Ennis has 
suffered kidney damage. 
</P>
<P>
 Authorities said there was no information about any suspects in the case. 
Officials at the Antelope Valley Sheriff's Station told reporters on Friday 
that they believed the incident to be a misguided prank and not a murder 
attempt. 
</P>
