<HEADLINE>
<P>
CITY ARTS; MINDING YOUR BUSINESS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By IRIS YOKOI 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 There will be exhibits of interest to small-business owners, aspiring 
entrepreneurs and consumers at the sixth annual Black Business Expo next 
Saturday and Sunday at the Los Angeles Convention Center. 
</P>
<P>
 More than 350 vendors, including financial institutions, health care 
providers, home improvement experts, artists and others, will exhibit their 
products and services. 
</P>
<P>
 Visitors can also get tips on everything from how to avoid injury on the job 
to how to buy a home at some of the 50 seminars and workshops throughout the 
weekend. 
</P>
<P>
 Musical entertainment will also be provided, with rhythm and blues and jazz 
groups performing. 
</P>
<P>
 The expo was established to support the development and marketing of 
black-owned businesses. 
</P>
<P>
 Based on last year's attendance, organizers expect 20,000 to 30,000 people 
from all over Southern California to check out this year's event, which has as 
its theme: "Keeping the Dream Alive in the Spirit of Unity." 
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 The Black Business Expo, 11 a.m. to 7 p.m. Saturday and April 17 at the Los 
Angeles Convention Center, 1202 S. Figueroa St. $6 admission; coupons for $2 
off admission are available at various businesses and community centers; (310) 
572-7555.  
</P>
<P>
 IRIS YOKOI 
</P>
