<HEADLINE>
<P>
ORANGE COUNTY NEWSWATCH 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Jerry Hicks and Shelby Grad 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 LONG ABSENTEES: They'll be going to the polls in Irvine on April 26, but it 
takes exclusive qualifications to vote in this election. South Africa will let 
its citizens living in the U.S. vote in its intense general election that day. 
Irvine City Hall was selected locally for its centralized location. . . . The 
county's South African population numbers about 3,000. Says one Irvine South 
African: "Everybody I know plans to be there. We're quite excited." 
</P>
<P>
 YOUNG & ITALIAN: If you're at Carmelo's Ristorante in Corona del Mar this 
afternoon, you'll get a surprise at how young the waiters are. And the 
hostesses. And the cooks. . . . They're all from nearby Corona del Mar High 
School, and owner Carmelo Manto will turn his dining room over to them. Manto 
says it's so "the youngsters can do something fun and get a 
behind-the-scenes-look at the restaurant business." The students see another 
bonus: The school gets to keep the profits from its two-hour stint. 
</P>
<P>
 IMAGINE TIME: If you think art means anything from finger painting to full 
orchestration, the county's Department of Education and the Orange County 
Performing Arts Center say they've got the thing for you. They call it 
Imagination Celebration. It starts Saturday. After that it runs April 23-May 1, 
nearly 40 art-related events countywide. . . . You'll see a lot of the poster 
by Heather Wilson, 17, of El Modena High, who won its contest with her idea 
that imagination is a world where "animals can fly a plane." 
</P>
<P>
 STARTING EARLY: Would you go to a college student to help you with something 
as complicated as exports or real estate? Liang Meng, 21, a Chapman University 
senior, isn't your average student. A straight A scholar, he's built an 
impressive list of clients who pay for his investment advice -- including some 
of the university's own trustees. The past week he was named Chapman's 
outstanding business and economics student. Says Meng, a native of Shanghai: 
"The faculty here really pays attention to the students." 
</P>
</TEXT>
