<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIGEST: GRAY BECOMES THIRD RECRUIT TO PICK CSUN FOR BASKETBALL 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By MIKE HISERMAN 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Eric Gray, a 6-foot-6 forward from Canada College in Redwood City, Calif., has 
orally committed to accept a basketball scholarship to Cal State Northridge. 
</P>
<P>
 Gray, accurate from long range, is the third recruit to choose 
Northridge.Reseda High guard Trenton Cross and Thousand Oaks High center Paul 
Brandt signed with the Matadors in November. 
</P>
<P>
 Gray averaged 19.9 points and seven rebounds for Canada, which finished 17-13, 
10-6 in the Coast Conference. In conference play, he made 40 of 99 three-point 
attempts. He scored more than 30 points three times, with a high of 38. 
</P>
<P>
 Northridge coaches privately have compared Gray to Keith Gibbs, the Matadors' 
scoring leader in the 1991-92 season. 
</P>
<P>
 Like Gibbs, Gray chose Northridge over mostly small-college competition. 
</P>
<P>
 "I wanted to play Division I," said Gray, who also was courted by Cal Poly 
Pomona and UC Davis. "Plus, I wanted to go back to Southern California so my 
parents could see me play." 
</P>
<P>
 Gray grew up in Twentynine Palms, where his family still resides. Bowling  
</P>
<P>
 Eric Forkel of Chatsworth lost his only match in Saturday's stepladder finals 
to finish in third place in the $250,000 BPAA U.S. Open bowling tournament in 
Troy, Mich. 
</P>
<P>
 Forkel, who qualified second, was defeated by Parker Bohn III, 228-202. 
Basketball  
</P>
<P>
 Jordan O'Gilvie scored 13 points, including all six of his team's points in 
overtime, as Tarzana Bantam defeated Woodland Hills, 42-39, to win the boys' 
10-year-old division Valley regional championship of the Los Angeles Parks and 
Recreation Department. T.J. Stephens led Tarzana with 17 rebounds and 10 
points. MIKE HISERMAN 
</P>
</TEXT>
